1. Java Code (LoginWeb.java)
(Create this file. It sets up a web page at Port 9090.)

Java
import com.sun.net.httpserver.*;
import java.net.InetSocketAddress;
import java.io.*;

public class LoginWeb {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Create server on Port 9090
        HttpServer server = HttpServer.create(new InetSocketAddress(9090), 0);
        
        server.createContext("/", ex -> {
            String res = "<html><body><h2>Login</h2><form method='POST'>User: <input name='u'><br>Pass: <input name='p'><br><input type='submit'></form></body></html>";
            
            if ("POST".equals(ex.getRequestMethod())) {
                String body = new String(ex.getRequestBody().readAllBytes());
                // Simple password check (User: admin, Pass: 123)
                if (body.contains("admin") && body.contains("123")) {
                    res = "<h1>Login Successful</h1>";
                } else {
                    res = "<h1>Access Denied</h1>";
                }
            }
            
            ex.sendResponseHeaders(200, res.length());
            ex.getResponseBody().write(res.getBytes());
            ex.getResponseBody().close();
        });
        
        server.start();
        System.out.println("Server started on Port 9090");
    }
}
2. Dockerfile
(We use the Java 17 trick to skip compilation and keep it short.)

Dockerfile
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jdk
COPY LoginWeb.java .
CMD ["java", "LoginWeb.java"]
3. Build & Run Commands (Use sudo!)
Build the Image:

Bash
sudo docker build -t login-web .
Run with Port Mapping (Crucial):

You MUST use -p 9090:9090. This connects your laptop's port to the Docker container's port.

Bash
sudo docker run -p 9090:9090 login-web
